		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName> <date>31 October 1853</date></p>
				<p>My Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Yours of the <date>27th</date> I recd with the<lb/> <date>Oct</date> Occidents which came in tolerable good season</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I enclose herein the Amount of my collections<lb/> up to this date&#44; the moment the business season<lb/> closes I will endeavor to collect mine and send<lb/> same to you as I have no doubt that it will be<lb/> useful whilst so much engaged in publications</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The most favorable season for the<lb/> disposal of your prayer Books would be during<lb/> the Autumn Holidays&#44; when there is usually an<lb/> anxiety to have Books&#45;possibly they may be<lb/> inquired for again in <date>Passover</date> but not to such<lb/> an extent as for <date>Atonement</date>.  It would be well<lb/> could your edition be made as portable &#38; small<lb/> as the English.  It seems very unfortunate<lb/> that you should not have complied with <persName>Mr<lb/> De Sola&#39;s</persName> request&#8212;to return to him his manuscript<lb/> unless published in <date>October</date> Number.  He states<lb/> his confidence of having written his wishes quite</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>distinctly.  I must admit his right to the return of<lb/> the document&#8212;if you found yourself unable to insert<lb/>  it as directed.  However as you will refrain from<lb/> adding any remarks of your own should you insert<lb/> his answer in the <date>Novr.</date> Occident&#44; now on the way to us<lb/> if is useless discussing the matter any further&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">You would not review <persName>Mr Raphael</persName> book because<lb/> you deemed it unworthy of a favorable notice&#44; but<lb/> you had no such hesitation as regards <persName>Mr Desolas</persName> you admit In this I can only see an absence of all anxiety to &#8220;satisfy people&#8221;  As you have often derived <del>in</del> having<lb/> been a Candidate for reelection by your late congregation<lb/> I cannot understand how you <sic>shuld</sic> consider enemies<lb/> those who vote for avowed candidates or why you should exhibit<lb/> such enmity towards those who have been Candidates.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr Morais</persName> seems to <add>&#63;</add> himself to give satisfaction to all and to be at enmity with none&#8212;these<lb/> qualities&#44; no doubt&#44; secured him the support of <persName>Mr Jratz<add>&#63;</add></persName><lb/> and will possibly obtain for him a life election.<lb/>  You must admit that it is but natural for a<lb/> congregation to retain the services of a Minister who<lb/> is popular with all.  If <persName>Mr Desola</persName> were at enmity<lb/> with three members of his congregation they vote<lb/> could keep him in&#44; I would not give it to him.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Our weather has been delightful with little cold.</p>
			<pb n="2R"/>
				<p>3</p>
				<p>I suppose you will not travel northward this<lb/> season.  <persName>Mr Joseph</persName> &#38; family are quite family<add>&#63;</add><lb/> she desires her best regards to you.  My mother is<lb/> as well as could be expected</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">If I can get suitable Bills I will endure<lb/> here in twenty one dollar of which&#44; the following<lb/> are to be acknowledged w next <sic>oxident</sic><lb/> say <add>&#63;</add>.  <persName>Desola</persName> &#38; <persName>Mr Joseph</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I expect to be in <placeName>New York</placeName> for one day<lb/> this week.  Believe me Ever</p>
			<p rend="indent(8)">Yrs Truly</p>
